  "prompt": "What is the difference between interim and ad interim order?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between interim and ad interim orders:\n\nInterim Order:\n1. Temporary order passed during ongoing legal proceedings\n2. Provides immediate relief or protection\n3. Can be modified or vacated later\n4. Typically used in civil and criminal cases\n5. Remains in force until final judgment or further order\n6. Requires prima facie satisfaction of legal requirements\n\nAd Interim Order:\n1. Literally means \"in the meantime\" or \"temporary\"\n2. More immediate and urgent relief\n3. Typically issued without notice to the other party\n4. Very short-term in nature\n5. Usually granted ex parte (without hearing the other side)\n6. Requires strong prima facie case and irreparable injury\n7. Typically used in situations demanding immediate intervention\n\nKey Distinctions:\n- Ad interim orders are more time-sensitive and urgent\n- Ad interim orders are usually passed without hearing the opposite party\n- Interim orders can be passed after hearing both parties\n- Ad interim orders have a more restricted scope and shorter duration\n- Interim orders have broader application across legal proceedings\n\nBoth serve to provide temporary relief during legal processes, but ad interim orders are more immediate and restrictive in nature.",
